    "# vis-foundation

Pkg: `com.blockether/vis-foundation`. Src: `extensions/common/vis-foundation/`.
Canonical: inlined under `[v :docs \"README.md\"]` in `META-INF/vis-extension/vis.edn`. LLM reads via `(v/extension-readme 'v)`.

ONE alias `v/` bundles everything the agent needs to read its own state, work the filesystem, build answer markdown, and see the host environment. It replaces the older split across separate aliases and keeps the model inside one short prefix for the whole iteration.

## Sections

### Introspection (read your own state)

Pure reads off the same DB tables the projection layer uses; failures return nil/[] never throw. Conversation-state introspection is intentionally a deep two-call surface: one canonical data map, one Markdown renderer over the same data.

```clojure
(v/inspect cid?)                ; canonical state data {:conversation :current-turn :failures :diagnosis :llm-diagnostics :transcript ...}
(v/report cid?)                 ; Markdown report rendered from the same state data, incl. raw LLM diagnostics
(v/extensions)                  ; loaded ext catalog incl. author/owner/license/source markers
(v/extension-docs ext-ref)      ; manifest doc summaries (no content)
(v/extension-doc ext-ref)       ; full README descriptor incl. :content
(v/extension-readme ext-ref)    ; README :content shortcut
(v/symbol-docs ext-ref)         ; sandbox symbol summaries
(v/symbol-doc ext-ref sym)      ; doc/arglists/examples for one sandbox symbol
```

### File I/O (structured helpers + babashka.fs wrappers)

Structured helpers return tool-result envelopes; the thin babashka.fs wrappers return ordinary Clojure values like strings, booleans, and line vectors.

```clojure
(v/cat path)                    ; -> {:ok? :result :markdown ...}
(v/cat path opts)               ; opts {:offset N :limit M :char-limit C}
(v/ls path)                     ; -> {:ok? :result {:children [...]} ...}
(v/ls path opts)                ; opts {:depth :hidden? :respect-gitignore?}
(v/rg [\"a\" \"b\"] path)       ; -> {:ok? :result {:hits [...]} ...}
                                  ; patterns = non-empty vec of LITERAL substrings (PCRE metacharacters auto-escaped)
                                  ; for genuine regex: (re-seq #\"...\" (str/join \"\\n\" (v/read-all-lines path)))
(v/bash command)                ; -> {:ok? true :result {:exit :stdout :stderr ...} ...}
(v/bash command opts)           ; opts {:cwd :timeout-ms :max-output-chars :stdin}

(v/read-all-lines path)         ; -> {:ok? true :result [\"line\" ...] ...}
(v/write-lines path lines)      ; -> {:ok? true :result \"path\" ...}
(v/update-file path f & xs)     ; -> {:ok? true :result new-string ...}
(v/create-dirs path)            ; -> {:ok? true :result \"path\" ...}
(v/list-dir path)               ; -> {:ok? true :result [\"child\" ...] ...}
(v/glob root pattern)           ; -> {:ok? true :result [\"match\" ...] ...}
(v/copy src dest)               ; -> {:ok? true :result \"dest\" ...}
(v/move src dest)               ; -> {:ok? true :result \"dest\" ...}
(v/delete path)                 ; -> {:ok? true :result true ...}
(v/delete-if-exists path)       ; -> {:ok? true :result true|false ...}
(v/exists? path)                ; -> {:ok? true :result true|false ...}
(v/cwd)                         ; -> \"/abs/path\"
(v/parent path)                 ; -> \"dir\" | nil
(v/file-name path)              ; -> \"file.ext\"
(v/extension path)              ; -> \"ext\"
(v/relativize from to)          ; -> \"relative/path\"
```

For structured Clojure edits use the sibling `vis-language-clojure` extension (alias `z/`).

### Markdown answer builders

Programmatic markdown for `(answer …)`. Pure string builders; no templating, no Mustache, no hidden interpolation layer.

```clojure
(v/h1 \"Patch report\")
(v/p \"Three files touched.\")
(v/table [\"file\" \"+/-\"] [[\"core.clj\" \"+12 / -4\"]])
(v/file-link \"src/core.clj\" 142)
(v/code-block \"(println :done)\" \"clojure\")
(v/join (v/h1 \"Done\") (v/p \"Ready.\"))

(answer
  (v/join
    (v/h1 \"Patch report\")
    (v/p \"Three files touched.\")
    (v/ul [\"Run verify.sh\" \"Update CHANGELOG\"])))
```

See `docs/src/extensions/common/markdown.md` for the full builder reference.

### Environment awareness

Bounded host + git + language + monorepo snapshot, computed lazily and cached per cwd.

```clojure
(v/snapshot)        ; full snapshot {:host :git :languages :monorepo}
(v/git)             ; git submap or nil
(v/languages)       ; bounded language scan
(v/monorepo)        ; monorepo shape detection
(v/render)          ; same render as the system prompt's `<environment>` block
(v/refresh!)        ; drop cache, recompute; useful after substantial working-tree changes
```

The `<environment>` block in the system prompt (cwd / user / platform / shell / locale / jvm / git / languages / monorepo) is rendered from the same snapshot. Drop this jar -> drop the block.

## Why one alias?

Pre-merge the agent had to context-switch between multiple aliases just to compose a single thought. Those boundaries reflected packaging history, not the model's actual job. Collapsing everything to `v/` keeps every primitive one short prefix away, including answer construction, so iteration code reads more like prose and less like namespace shuffling."
